47. "The superior man does not, even for the space of a single meal, act contrary to virtue."
48. "The superior man is firm in the right way, and not merely firm."
49. "The superior man is dignified but does not wrangle, affable but not adulatory."
50. "The superior man is affable, but not adulatory; the mean man is adulatory, but not affable."
51. "The superior man cannot be known in little matters but may be entrusted with great concerns."
52. "The superior man does what is proper to the station in which he is; he does not desire to go beyond this."
53. "The superior man has a dignified ease without pride. The mean man has pride without a dignified ease."
54. "The superior man is satisfied and composed; the mean man is always full of distress."
